    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>For Copper Plaintiffs, the Venue Is Peru</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Bloomberg Business News</byline>
      <dateline>CORPUS CHRISTI, Tex., Jan. 25</dateline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The Southern Peru Copper Company won dismissal today of a lawsuit filed in United States District Court here by hundreds of Peruvians who accused the company of pollution. Judge Janis Graham Jack ruled that Federal and international law required that the case be tried in Peru.</p>
        <p>Also named in the suit, filed in August, were Asarco Inc. of New York, which owns 51 percent of Southern Peru Copper, and the Phelps Dodge Corporation of Phoenix and the Newmont Mining Corporation of Denver, minority shareholders in Southern Peru Copper.</p>
      </block>
